    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Willow Vale, | Frome.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Oct 3. 80</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>A case occurred in my practice a short time ago of sudden death in a girl aged 16 years—</p>
<p>She had been apparently well, till a minute before death when she suddenly became collapsed with violent pain in the abdomen, &amp; was dead before her companion could fetch help— At the P.M.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> I found a large abscess (entirely unsuspected during life) had burst into the peritoneal cavity, in the centre of it was a cherry stone which had worked through a ragged hole in the vermiform appendage of the cæcum— In re-reading your Descent of Man (Edit 2. p. 20–21) I thought this short record might be interesting to you as bearing on a statement there made.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
                    <p>I trust you will forgive the presumption of an entire stranger writing to you on so small a point and believe me to be  | Yours respectfully | Frederick Parsons</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">‘P.M.’: post-mortem.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">In <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1967.xml"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi> 2d ed.</ref>, pp. 20–1, CD had discussed the vermiform appendage of the caecum (the appendix), and how small hard bodies such as seeds could cause death by entering it and causing inflammation.</note>
        </div>
    
